Okay, so I'd write something like this:

```rust
#[cfg(target_os = "linux")] fn read_file_linux(path: &str) -> Result<String, io::Error> {
  // Linux-specific logic
}

#[cfg(target_os = "windows")] fn read_file_windows(path: &str) -> Result<String, io::Error> {
  // Windows-specific logic
}
```

Yes! That way you can write portable code with OS-specific features seamlessly. And if you want to make your tests cross-platform, you can use #[cfg_attr] on tests like so:

```rust
#[cfg(test)]
#[cfg_attr(target_os = "linux", test)]
fn test_read_file_linux() {
  // Linux test logic
}
```
This way, the test will only run when targeting Linux.

Good question! `cfg_if!` is often cleaner when you have multiple configurations and want to avoid nested if-else chains. It looks like this:

```rust
cfg_if::cfg_if! {
  if #[cfg(target_os = "linux")] { ... }
  else if #[cfg(target_os = "windows")] { ... }
  else { ... }
}
```
This keeps your logic more readable and avoids repetition.

